Question 3

95% CI for \(\beta_1\): 3 \(\pm\) 2(1.3) = (.4, 5.6); \(\beta_1\) is statistically significantly different from 0.

It is extremely unlikely that X and Y are not related.

Question 4

One additional year of education is associated with a 76.2-hour increase in annual work when adjusting for number of children under 5.

Standard error on the children under 5 coefficient is 19.7 hours when not adjusting for education.

A woman with no children under 5 and no years of education is expected to work 306.6 hours annually.

3,382 observations are used in each model.

Yes, in both models in which its included (2 and 3) its significant at the 99% level (and so also at the 95% level).

Question 5

One year increase in YearsEducation produces a 110.23 - 3.162(YearsEducation) change in HoursWorked.

If YearsEducation is 16, a one year increase in YearsEducation would produce a 56.5-point increase in HoursWorked.

The relationship is getting less positive as YearsEducation increases.

We dont want to overfit our model to the data.

For every unit increase of humidity, the probability of detecting dengue fever increases by .05.

Coding Question 9

Shot in the dark: logging the dependent variable makes sense when an increase in X causes a percent change in Y instead of a straight unit change. One could imagine that the difference between 0 and 30 degrees Fahrenheit should matter less for humidity than the difference between 60 and 90 degrees Fahrenheit; in an unlogged model, they would count the same. Also, conveniently, there are no 0s in humidity, so the log transformation is easy.
